- Introduction:¶

1. Dataset Description¶

  • The Dataset contains many information about Movies helpful to be analyzed. The Data is collected from 1960 till the year 2015.

2. Analysis Questions¶

  1. What are the most popular genres?
  2. Who directed most of the movies?
  3. Which company produced most of the movies?
  4. The most famous cast member (that depends on how many films each produced)
  5. How many genres, directors, companies and cast members contributed to the Movie industy from 1960 to 2015)?
  6. The relation between genres and popularity
  7. Does runtime affects vote_average?
  8. The most liked production_companies based on vote_average
  9. The relation between release_year and ( [budget_adj, revenue_adj],popularity, vote_average)
  10. What takes the most runtime in genres?
  11. How many cast members and directors contribute for better vote_average?
  12. What affects Revenue_adj?

df_clean_c=df.copy()                                        #Collecting info about genres, cast, direcotors and cast columns
df_clean_c.dropna(inplace=True, subset=['cast'])            #While deleting NaN values to avoid errors
df_clean_c['cast']= df_clean_c['cast'].apply(lambda x: x.split('|'))
cast_dict={}
for cast in df_clean_c['cast']:
    for c in cast:
        if c not in cast_dict:
            cast_dict[c]=1
        if c in cast_dict:
            cast_dict[c]+=1            
df_clean_cd=df_clean_c.copy()     
df_clean_cd.dropna(inplace=True,subset=['director'])
df_clean_cd['director']=df_clean_cd['director'].apply(lambda x: x.split('|'))
directors_dict={}
for directors in df_clean_cd['director']:
    for d in directors:
        if d not in directors_dict:
            directors_dict[d] =1
        if d in directors_dict:
            directors_dict[d]+=1
df_clean_cdg=df_clean_cd.copy()                                            #Trying to lessen the ammount of removed rows of             
df_clean_cdg.dropna(inplace=True,subset=['genres'])                        #NaN to ensure high quality details 
df_clean_cdg['genres']=df_clean_cdg['genres'].apply(lambda x: x.split('|'))
genres_dict={}
for genre in df_clean_cdg['genres']:
    for g in genre:
        if g not in genres_dict:
            genres_dict[g] =1
        if g in genres_dict:
            genres_dict[g]+=1
df_clean_cdgp=df_clean_cdg.copy()    
df_clean_cdgp.dropna(inplace=True, subset=['production_companies']) #I dropped NaN values here, due to the huge number of
df_clean_cdgp['production_companies']=df_clean_cdgp['production_companies'].apply(lambda x: x.split('|'))
companies_dict={}                                    #NaN values present in this column, so it would not 
for companies in df_clean_cdgp['production_companies']:       #affect the info got from genres/directors/cast .
    for c in companies:
        if c not in companies_dict:
            companies_dict[c]= 1
        if c in companies_dict:
            companies_dict[c]+=1   
            
companies_dict2={}    
for companies in df_clean_cdgp['production_companies']:       #affect the info got from genres/directors/cast .
    for c in companies:
        if c not in companies_dict2:
            companies_dict2[c]= df_clean_cdgp[df_clean_cdgp['production_companies']==c]['vote_average'].sum()
        if c in companies_dict2:
            companies_dict2[c]+=df_clean_cdgp[df_clean_cdgp['production_companies']==c]['vote_average'].sum()  

                                                            #I didn't use a def function due to the number of modified variables 
                                                            #I needed like df_clean_c/cd/cdg/cdgp. I made them specifically to
                                                            #Avoid deleting useful info in the rows about to be deleted.
genres_tuple=tuple(genres_dict)
directors_tuple=tuple(directors_dict)
companies_tuple=tuple(companies_dict)
cast_tuple=tuple(cast_dict)

def top3(dict_name):
    for top in sorted(dict_name.values())[-3:]:
        x=print(list(dict_name.keys())[list(dict_name.values()).index(top)])
    return x
  • I left null rows of imdb_id as they are, due to no correlation between other columns. Same goes for many other rows of different columns, except for cast so to append it to the cast_list, same goes for other newly created lists.

Conclusions¶

  • ### Revenue is affected by:

    1. Average-Vote

      • Runtime from 100-170 correlates with better Average-Vote & Revenue. (Q.12 & 7)*
      • Directors starting from (Christopher Nolan, Joss Whedon, James Cameron) are correlated with more Average-Vote.
      • Cast, there are no specific correlation for each cast member with Average-Vote, but there's the all time best combination of cast members shown in Q.11. (Q.11)
      • Genres of (Drama, War, History) correlate with better Average-Vote. (Q.10)
      • Production-Companies starting from (Universal Pictures, Warner Bros, Paramount Pictures) correlate with more Average-Vote. (Q.8)

    2. Budget

      • More Budget correlates with better Revenues. 1.3 to 2 correlates with less losses. (Q.12)
        • If successful, there is a probability that the Revenue is double the Budget. (Q.9)
      • Budget from 0 to 0.4 are a budget for most of the movies. (Q.14)
    3. Popularity
      • Genres starting from (Drama, Comedy, Action) correlate with more Popularity. (Q.6)
      • Popularity from 4 to 6 correlate with more revenue income, yet it is not for sure. (Q.12)
    4. Runtime
      • Runtime from 100-170 correlates with better Average-Vote & Revenue. (Q.12 & 7)*

  • ##### Revenue is affected by them descendingly (Q.12) :

    1. Popularity
    2. Runtime
    3. Budget
    4. Vote-Average

  • ##### Income varies from (-0.5 to 1.5) yet there should be no worries about the movie-failiure as it deemed less probable. (Q.13)

Limitations¶

- There was no solid correlation between Runtime & Income. (Q.12)
- There was no strong correlation between Budget & Revenue. (Q.12)
- Vote-Averages seem to be declining with time, so contribution to a better Vote-Average would increase the chances of         revenue as they correlate positively. (Q.9)
